Post-hoc interactions using emmeans

  • Treatment A vs.Â (Treatment B, Treatment C)

  • is there a diff between those two chunks, across hospitals?

  • basically kind of compresses data into a 2x2 design

Get estimated marginal means

Create manual contrasts for each of the things we want to compare.

Step by step from before, end up with

treat_contrast <- c(
  'TreatA' = 1,
  'TreatB' = -1/2,
  'TreatC' = -1/2
)

hosp_contrast <- c(
  'Hosp1' = 1,
  'Hosp2' = -1
)

Get outer product (actually show table and fill in cell by cell)

ixn_contrast <- outer(treat_contrast, hosp_contrast)

Before we used levels() to get the order, because we were only looking at one variable. Now weâ€™ve got interplay between two variables, so weâ€™ll just base things on the order they appear in the emmeans table here.

ixn_comp <- list(
  "A vs. BC in diff Hospitals" = 
    c(
      1,     # TreatA Hosp1 
      -1/2,  # TreatB Hosp1
      -1/2,  # TreatC Hosp1
      -1,    # TreatA Hosp2
      1/2,   # TreatB Hosp2
      1/2    # TreatC Hosp2
    )
)

Test the contrast using contrast() from emmeans.

ixn_contrast_test <- contrast(m1_emm, ixn_comp)
ixn_contrast_test
 contrast                   estimate    SE  df t.ratio p.value
 A vs. BC in diff Hospitals     3.73 0.641 174   5.819  <.0001

We can reject the H0 that thereâ€™s no difference between hospitals in the effectiveness of A vs.Â BC. Symmetrically, we can reject the H0 that the relationship between A vs.Â BC is the same in both hospitals.

Where does this number 3.73 come from?

Itâ€™s the sum of all of the group means, each multiplied by the coding from our matrix.

ixn_contrast
       Hosp1 Hosp2
TreatA   1.0  -1.0
TreatB  -0.5   0.5
TreatC  -0.5   0.5
1 * mean_A1 +
  -1   * mean_A2 +
  -0.5 * mean_B1 +
   0.5 * mean_B2 +
  -0.5 * mean_C1 +
   0.5 * mean_C2
[1] 3.728333

Itâ€™s positive, so that means that the means that received positive weights are bigger than the means that received negative weights.
